concept_explanation.index_out_of_bounds:
**The #1 array bug**: accessing an invalid index.

```java
int[] scores = {85, 90, 78, 92, 88};  // valid: 0-4

System.out.println(scores[5]);   // CRASH: ArrayIndexOutOfBoundsException
System.out.println(scores[-1]);  // CRASH: same error
```

This is a RUNTIME error, not a compile error. The compiler doesn't check index validity. You'll see it crash mid-execution.

**Off-by-one is common**:

```java
// WRONG: goes one too far
for (int i = 0; i <= scores.length; i++) {  // <= instead of <
    System.out.println(scores[i]);  // Crashes when i = 5
}

// RIGHT:
for (int i = 0; i < scores.length; i++) {  // < is correct
    System.out.println(scores[i]);
}
```

**Defensive pattern**: check bounds before accessing:

```java
if (i >= 0 && i < scores.length) {
    System.out.println(scores[i]);
} else {
    System.out.println("Invalid index");
}
```

Useful when index comes from user input or computation.

concept_explanation.arrays_are_objects:
Important Java fact: **arrays are OBJECTS**, not primitives. When you 'assign' an array to a new variable, you're copying the REFERENCE (the address), not the data.

```java
int[] a = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};
int[] b = a;          // b now REFERS to the same array as a
b[0] = 999;
System.out.println(a[0]);  // 999! Same array, modified through b
```

This is a critical concept that confuses many beginners. `int[] b = a` does NOT copy. It makes `b` point to the same array `a` points to. Changes through either variable affect both.

To actually COPY an array, use `Arrays.copyOf` (we'll cover this later) or a loop:

```java
int[] b = new int[a.length];
for (int i = 0; i < a.length; i++) {
    b[i] = a[i];
}
// Now b is a true copy
```

For now, just be aware: array assignment shares references. Object behavior gets fully covered in OOP module.

**Implication for methods**: when you pass an array to a method, the method gets the same reference — modifications inside DO affect the original:

```java
public static void modify(int[] arr) {
    arr[0] = 999;  // affects the caller's array!
}

public static void main(String[] args) {
    int[] nums = {1, 2, 3};
    modify(nums);
    System.out.println(nums[0]);  // 999
}
```

Different from primitives (which are passed by value). For arrays/objects: modifications inside methods affect the caller's array.

concept_explanation.common_patterns:
Three patterns you'll use constantly:

**1. Sum/total** (accumulator with array):

```java
int[] nums = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};
int sum = 0;
for (int n : nums) {
    sum += n;
}
System.out.println("Sum: " + sum);  // 150
```

**2. Find max/min**:

```java
int[] nums = {10, 25, 7, 42, 18};
int max = nums[0];  // start with first element
for (int n : nums) {
    if (n > max) {
        max = n;
    }
}
System.out.println("Max: " + max);  // 42
```

Why start with `nums[0]` instead of 0? Because 0 might be larger than all elements (e.g., all negative numbers). Starting with the first element is safe.

**3. Search for a value**:

```java
int[] nums = {10, 25, 7, 42, 18};
int target = 42;
boolean found = false;
for (int n : nums) {
    if (n == target) {
        found = true;
        break;
    }
}
System.out.println("Found: " + found);
```

These three patterns appear in 80% of array problems. Master them and you've handled most exercises.

step_by_step_solution.details:
Start with the array literal and a basic main:

```java
public class SalesReport {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        double[] dailySales = {4500, 6200, 3800, 7100, 5400, 8900, 4200};

        // Process and print...
    }
}
```

We use `double[]` because sales could have decimals in real data (₹4500.50 etc.).

7 elements. Indexes 0-6. We'll process each.

We need both the value AND the index (day number is index + 1). Classic for loop fits:

```java
System.out.println("=== Daily Sales ===");
for (int i = 0; i < dailySales.length; i++) {
    System.out.println("Day " + (i + 1) + ": ₹" + dailySales[i]);
}
```

Note `(i + 1)` for human-friendly day numbering. The parens are important — without them, you'd get string concatenation: 'Day 01:', 'Day 11:', etc. With parens: 'Day 1:', 'Day 2:'.

For total, we just need each value — for-each is cleaner:

```java
double total = 0;
for (double sale : dailySales) {
    total += sale;
}
System.out.println("\nTotal: ₹" + total);
```

Classic accumulator pattern from Module 1. Start at 0, add each element.

**Why for-each here?** We don't need the index. Just summing values. Cleaner.

Total: 4500 + 6200 + 3800 + 7100 + 5400 + 8900 + 4200 = 40,100

Track the maximum value AND its index (so we can report which day):

```java
double maxSale = dailySales[0];
int bestDayIndex = 0;
for (int i = 1; i < dailySales.length; i++) {
    if (dailySales[i] > maxSale) {
        maxSale = dailySales[i];
        bestDayIndex = i;
    }
}
System.out.println("Best Day: Day " + (bestDayIndex + 1) + " with ₹" + maxSale);
```

Start at index 1 (since index 0 is the initial 'max'). For each element, if it's bigger, update both max and the index where it occurred.

**Why we need the index**: to report 'Day 6 was the best,' we need to know it was at index 5.

For our data: 8900 at index 5 is the max → Day 6.

Mirror of max:

```java
double minSale = dailySales[0];
int worstDayIndex = 0;
for (int i = 1; i < dailySales.length; i++) {
    if (dailySales[i] < minSale) {
        minSale = dailySales[i];
        worstDayIndex = i;
    }
}
System.out.println("Worst Day: Day " + (worstDayIndex + 1) + " with ₹" + minSale);
```

For our data: 3800 at index 2 is the min → Day 3.

worked_example.final_code:
public class SalesReport {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        double[] dailySales = {4500, 6200, 3800, 7100, 5400, 8900, 4200};

        System.out.println("=== Daily Sales Report ===");

        // Print each day
        for (int i = 0; i < dailySales.length; i++) {
            System.out.println("Day " + (i + 1) + ": ₹" + dailySales[i]);
        }

        // Calculate total
        double total = 0;
        for (double sale : dailySales) {
            total += sale;
        }

        // Find best day
        double maxSale = dailySales[0];
        int bestDayIndex = 0;
        for (int i = 1; i < dailySales.length; i++) {
            if (dailySales[i] > maxSale) {
                maxSale = dailySales[i];
                bestDayIndex = i;
            }
        }

        // Find worst day
        double minSale = dailySales[0];
        int worstDayIndex = 0;
        for (int i = 1; i < dailySales.length; i++) {
            if (dailySales[i] < minSale) {
                minSale = dailySales[i];
                worstDayIndex = i;
            }
        }

        // Calculate average
        double average = total / dailySales.length;

        // Summary
        System.out.println("\n=== Summary ===");
        System.out.println("Total: ₹" + total);
        System.out.println("Best Day: Day " + (bestDayIndex + 1) + " with ₹" + maxSale);
        System.out.println("Worst Day: Day " + (worstDayIndex + 1) + " with ₹" + minSale);
        System.out.println("Average: ₹" + average);
    }
}

